 that it is how it works in real race as well :) ). You could also consider how much time a driver raced in a specific circuit to improve his/her level of experience.- the contract negotations are horrible! I understand that you have to pay a penalty if you take a driver/engineer from another team while the older contract is still running, but you should be able to close a contract for the future. And also I think that it would be better to have more staff than just an engineer and two mechanics: it would make more challenging having a five star team.- I would like to have more transparency to understand how the car for the next year will be influenced by the development of the car for the current one."
76561198076666056,Recommended,415200,31941151,Posted: 24 May,all,D.H Ginting,Bye bye real lifeRealLifeDestroyer/10
,Recommended,415200,26546681,"Posted: 11 November, 2016",all,KINE,"9/10 Management GameIf you like management games, this game is worth a tryIf you like F1 and not specifically just the driving, this game is worth a tryIf you like both F1 and management type games, you should obviously get thisPlenty to manage outside the track. Staff, car parts, scouting talent, driver, infrastructure, finances and sponsors etc. Decisions on race day are meaningful. One bad call can lose you your podium run. One inspired tactical change could leap frog your car from the middle all the way to the front. RNG is minimal. When things go wrong, you would've seen it coming so most things are calculated risks.Slick interface, nice art. Game flows smoothly taking you from one task to the next seamlessly. Despite the large number of screens and pages you need to look at, you rarely get lost or distracted. Nicely thought out. All the game's concepts are intuitive, the average person should be able to pick up what's going on, what needs doing and how to do them better quickly. Even without a tutorial this game is easy to understand.Teams voting on next season's ruleset is wonderful and adds much to the strategy. Love it. Team building strategic options are there. The long term game isn't linear. Players have options on how to improve their teams or more specifically, what to improve first with each choice affecting how your seasons will play out. That said, it is heavily dependent on financial resources thus playing poorer teams means less choices on how to proceed. Given the slow paced nature of Motorsport Manager, this can turn players off.Overall - managing a team in this game is both deep and satisfying.Things I didn't particularly liked and wished were different:- Gimmicky qualifying mechanics prolly there to keep grid starts a little less predictable. Not necessarily a bad thing but could've been done better. Auto resolving qualifying usually puts you at the back of the pack.- Practice session and fine tuning is fun. But UI on driver feedback could be improved. If you missed what your drivers said while they were driving, you're left guessing back at the pitstop which is annoying. And some effort could have been put into providing clues toward achieving perfect settings for all the categories. Right now, you're pretty much guessing blind.- Managing pit strategy for both your cars simultaneously on Race Day can be chaotic. Wished there were quality of life features to automate pitting your cars at predetermined intervals. As is, it's too easy to pit your cars too early or missing opportunistic pitstops when the safety car comes out all because you didn't see it in time.---25 hours played at time of writing.Started the game playing the challenge mode: Take a low tier team and top the constructor's table.Team was 8th of 10 at season start. Ended first season still at 8th.Now in season 2, averaging 6th place as manufacturer. Prolly end second season 5th.This gonna take a while.Motorsport Manager is definitely a long game."
